Key takeaways (auto-updated conceptually)

Use this panel to interpret spatial co-variation patterns. Focus on HH (orange) clusters as potential compound-risk hotspots.

  • HH areas indicate locations where both selected hazards are above their citywide mean (relative hotspots).
  • HL/LH show spatial mismatch: one hazard high while the other low—useful for targeted single-hazard interventions.
  • LL (gray) indicates relative low exposure for both hazards (baseline zones).
Risk Assessment (Grid-level)
RiskMean is displayed on the aligned PM2.5 grid. NA cells are removed (no purple background).

Interpreting HCMC climate-risk distribution

The grid-level risk surface reveals a clear spatial unevenness: higher risk clusters concentrate around the urbanized core and along development corridors, while lower-risk areas appear more fragmented.

  • Look for contiguous orange-tinted cells: these represent the upper quantiles of RiskMean and suggest compound stress zones.
  • Patchy transitions often reflect heterogeneous land cover, drainage conditions, and localized exposure differences within the same district.
  • Use district boundaries for governance alignment, but interpret risk at grid scale for actionable micro-targeting.

Hover any cell to read its RiskMean value. District boundary remains on top for orientation.

District-level Risk
Each district is colored by mean RiskMean aggregated from the same aligned risk grid (r_risk_rs).

How to read the district map

This view translates the grid-level risk surface into governance units. It is useful for policy prioritization, budgeting, and inter-district comparison.

  • A district’s color represents the average RiskMean of all valid risk cells within its boundary.
  • nCells indicates how many risk-valid grid cells contributed—use it as a confidence / coverage cue.
  • If a district looks homogeneous here but heterogeneous in Page 2, treat Page 2 as the operational layer.
